docs.abstract: A 60-year-old woman was killed and five others, including the suspect, were shot during a confrontation near the man’s house, the authorities said.

docs.lead_paragraph: PORTLAND, Ore. — A 43-year-old Portland man was charged with murder on Tuesday in a shooting during a weekend protest against police killings in which a woman was killed and five others including the suspect were wounded.

headline.main: Man Charged With Murder in Shooting at Protest in Portland
headline.print_headline: Man Charged With Murder in Portland Protest Shootings That Killed One

docs.abstract: The change at the top comes at an awkward moment for the Metropolitan Police Service: It is investigating the government for breaking lockdown rules and faces scrutiny for its own scandals.
docs.snippet: The change at the top comes at an awkward moment for the Metropolitan Police Service: It is investigating the government for breaking lockdown rules and faces scrutiny for its own scandals.
docs.lead_paragraph: LONDON — London’s police department was already dealing with a crisis of trust amid allegations of misogyny, racism and bullying when it became embroiled in a political drama. Last month, it opened an investigation into parties at Downing Street during lockdown that could determine Prime Minister Boris Johnson’s political fate.

headline.main: Troubled London Police Force Searches for a New Leader
headline.print_headline: London Police, Facing Crisis and Stuck in a Political Fight, Seek a New Leader

docs.abstract: Randa Abd Al-Aziz was joking with friends in a Baghdad cafe when she got a surprise job offer: broadcasting the news in Iraq, whose Black citizens have little media presence and even less power.
docs.snippet: Randa Abd Al-Aziz was joking with friends in a Baghdad cafe when she got a surprise job offer: broadcasting the news in Iraq, whose Black citizens have little media presence and even less power.
docs.lead_paragraph: BAGHDAD — Randa Abd Al-Aziz was relaxing in a Baghdad cafe, making her friends laugh by reading a cosmetics pamphlet aloud in classical Arabic, the exaggeratedly formal language of speeches, official decrees — and TV anchors.

headline.main: A Black Iraqi’s Sudden Career in TV News: ‘They Wanted to See All Colors’
headline.print_headline: A Fresh Face Breaks Barriers on Iraq’s State News Channel

docs.abstract: After the global reckoning over race in 2020, some group-tour providers made a pledge to improve equity through training, mentoring and funding for minority guides.
docs.snippet: After the global reckoning over race in 2020, some group-tour providers made a pledge to improve equity through training, mentoring and funding for minority guides.
docs.lead_paragraph: In late 2020, Leon Burnette, an independent tour director and civil rights historian, received a phone call from the director of a global travel company, asking him to recommend Black tour guides for a new tour being created along the United States Civil Rights Trail, which snakes from Kansas to Washington, D.C. But there was a problem: Mr. Burnette hardly knew any.

headline.main: Tour Companies Pledged to Address Racial Inequality. Those Promises Are Taking Shape.

docs.abstract: A stay-at-home mother deprived of an education, Damiana Nassar played a woman much like herself in “Feathers,” a Cannes winner that few in Egypt can see.
docs.snippet: A stay-at-home mother deprived of an education, Damiana Nassar played a woman much like herself in “Feathers,” a Cannes winner that few in Egypt can see.
docs.lead_paragraph: AL BARSHA, Egypt — When the star of “Feathers,” the most talked about — and critically acclaimed — Egyptian movie of the past year, showed up to shoot her first scenes, she had never acted before. She could not even read her lines.

headline.main: She Had Never Acted, and Could Barely Read. Now, She’s an Egyptian Movie Star.
headline.print_headline: Worker, Mother, Star: Egyptian Actress Pulls From Everyday Life

docs.abstract: President Biden’s visit to New York on Thursday is meant to convey his desire to respond to violent crime while guarding against the danger of excess policing.
docs.snippet: President Biden’s visit to New York on Thursday is meant to convey his desire to respond to violent crime while guarding against the danger of excess policing.
docs.lead_paragraph: Last summer, Eric Adams declared himself the “face” of the Democratic Party, pre-emptively seizing the national spotlight months before he took office as mayor of New York City. That spotlight fell directly on Mr. Adams on Thursday, as he hosted President Biden for a summit on public safety.

headline.main: For Biden and Adams, a Meeting of Like Minds on Gun Crime
headline.print_headline: Biden and Adams Convene a Meeting of Like Minds on Gun Violence

docs.abstract: Banks are raising pay to fend off investment firms, fintechs and crypto start-ups. Still, leaving is often about something other than “always having more and more.”
docs.snippet: Banks are raising pay to fend off investment firms, fintechs and crypto start-ups. Still, leaving is often about something other than “always having more and more.”
docs.lead_paragraph: It didn’t matter that Citigroup paid Amy Wu Stratton $450,000 in 2021 — her most lucrative year ever — to work with some of its biggest private equity clients. It didn’t even matter that she was on track for a promotion that could double her pay.

headline.main: Wall Street Opens Its Wallet to Keep Talent. It’s Not Always Enough.
headline.print_headline: As Wall St. Churns, Sometimes Money Isn’t Enough

docs.abstract: Ignored by the media and pushed aside by the police, families and supporters of Black women are building their own missing persons operations online.
docs.snippet: Ignored by the media and pushed aside by the police, families and supporters of Black women are building their own missing persons operations online.
docs.lead_paragraph: On Jan. 22, the night before Lauren Smith-Fields would have turned 24, her friends gathered to celebrate the birthday of another friend. They talked, listened to music. And then “Good Days” by SZA began to play.

headline.main: Why Lauren Smith-Fields’s Friends Turned to TikTok
headline.print_headline: The Police Failed to Act, So Her Friends Sought Justice on TikTok

docs.abstract: The Supreme Court justice and his wife battled for years for a more conservative America. New reporting shows how far she was willing to go after Donald Trump’s 2020 election loss.
docs.snippet: The Supreme Court justice and his wife battled for years for a more conservative America. New reporting shows how far she was willing to go after Donald Trump’s 2020 election loss.
docs.lead_paragraph: The call to action was titled “Election Results and Legal Battles: What Now?” Shared in the days after the 2020 presidential election, it urged the members of an influential if secretive right-wing group to contact legislators in three of the swing states that tipped the balance for Joe Biden — Arizona, Georgia and Pennsylvania. The aim was audacious: Keep President Donald J. Trump in power.

headline.main: The Long Crusade of Clarence and Ginni Thomas
headline.print_headline: The Long Crusade of Clarence and Ginni Thomas

byline.original: By Danny Hakim and Jo Becker
